I do see Elon Musk=E2=80=99s point. He runs, what, six companies? SpaceX, N=
euralink, Twitter/X, the tunnel one, xAI, probably some I=E2=80=99m forgett=
ing. And Tesla Inc., the only one of them that is public, though for a whil=
e he also had SolarCity Corp. before (controversially)   merging it into Te=
sla. Each of these companies does something different=E2=80=94=C2=A0rocket =
science, brain surgery, posting on the internet, tunnels, artificial intell=
igence, cars =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there is overlap.=C2=A0They seem to  share =
employees and a certain ambitious science fiction ethos, and you could imag=
ine futuristic projects that could be done at any of them.
At all but one of his companies, he could stroll into the boardroom, throw =
a big=C2=A0bag of ketamine down onto the table, and say =E2=80=9CI need the=
 company to spend $50 million to build a giant golden statue of me riding a=
 rocket,=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0and
=09the board would be like =E2=80=9Cyes definitely let=E2=80=99s do it,=E2=
=80=9D=09the board members themselves probably are, or represent, big share=
holders of the company, and as shareholders they would happily go along wit=
h the statue plan to keep Musk happy and dedicated to their company,=09the=
=C2=A0other=C2=A0shareholders, the ones without board seats, are probably e=
ven bigger   Musk fans, and are probably working on their own Musk statues =
in their garages anyway, so they=E2=80=99ll be fine with the company spendi=
ng their money on a corporate gold statue, and=09nobody else really has any=
 standing to complain.

And so in fact when Musk went to SpaceX and   asked to borrow $1 billion un=
til payday so that he could buy Twitter Inc., the board was like =E2=80=9Ch=
ere=E2=80=99s the check, we=E2=80=99ve left the amount blank, take whatever=
 you need.=E2=80=9D And, look, was there a  Wall Street Journal article say=
ing =E2=80=9Chey that=E2=80=99s weird=E2=80=9D? There was; it was weird. Di=
d anything come of that? No. SpaceX could just do that: Musk controls Space=
X, the board loves him, the shareholders love him, nobody in a position to =
complain has any complaints, and everybody else is in no position to compla=
in.
This is all at least arguably rational. The analysis is something like:
=09Elon Musk is an unusual cat, in some ways that make him really good at b=
uilding valuable and innovative companies, and in some ways that make him d=
ifficult and destructive,=C2=A0and also in some random ways that are just w=
eird. You can=E2=80=99t get just=C2=A0Good Elon; you take the good with the=
 bad with the random.=C2=A0=09He spends all of his time at work, apparently=
, at his various companies. But he probably does neglect some of the compan=
ies, at times, for the other ones. There are only 168 hours in the week and=
 he=E2=80=99s doing a lot of full-time jobs. And there=C2=A0are=C2=A0projec=
ts that you could imagine him doing at any of his companies.=C2=A0At least =
 Tesla, xAI and  Twitter/X seem to be working on artificial intelligence mo=
dels, for instance.=09His efforts appear to be=C2=A0extremely=C2=A0valuable=
 to those companies, creating surely hundreds of billions of dollars of=C2=
=A0 value for their shareholders.
  [2]

=09If he wants some weird thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0a hypothetical gold statue, =
a  flamethrower,   a glass mansion, a  pointless fight with a cave diver, T=
witter =E2=80=94 he will naturally ask one of his companies to help him get=
 it. If you work 168 hours a week running six companies, the distinction be=
tween your jobs and your personal life will blur, and if you want something=
 your first instinct might be to ask an employee to get it for you.=09If he=
 asks a company for something and it says no, he might sulk, or turn his at=
tention to his=C2=A0other=C2=A0companies, and stop working so hard on that =
company=E2=80=99s business.=C2=A0=09If you are a director or shareholder of=
 a Musk company, Musk=E2=80=99s love and attention is=C2=A0really valuable=
=C2=A0to you, worth possibly tens or hundreds of billions of dollars, and s=
o you want to give him whatever he wants to retain his affection.

This is a very unhealthy=C2=A0dynamic, in a lot of ways =E2=80=94=C2=A0he c=
an keep escalating his demands for more stuff! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does s=
eem rational. And even if you knew in advance that he would have this sort =
of holdup power, and that he=E2=80=99d use it, you might still sign up for =
the unhealthy dynamic, because he really has made a lot of shareholders a l=
ot of money, and they really would be happy to give him the gold statue and=
