ight want in exchange for even a fraction of his entrepreneurial attention.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there=E2=80=99s Tesla. Tesla in many =
ways is very similar to the other Musk companies. He is the quasi-founder, =
the visionary, the biggest shareholder, the chief executive officer. The bo=
ard loves him and will do anything he asks. The=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0=
</em>mostly love him and are big Elon Musk fans. He has created gazillions =
of dollars of value for shareholders and, somewhat reasonably, expects them=
 to be grateful.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are two big differences. One is that=
 Tesla is much=C2=A0<em>bigger=C2=A0</em>than the other Musk companies, so =
if he has a=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>big ask=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0if he wan=
ts, not a $50 million bauble, but a $50=C2=A0<em>billion=C2=A0</em>bauble =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0he has to go to Tesla, because it=E2=80=99s the only one of =
his companies that can afford to give it to him.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the other is that Tesla is a public compan=
y, which means that, even if 99% of shareholders love him, if 1% of shareho=
lders don=E2=80=99t, they can sue.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
