">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0They can say: =E2=80=9CLook, the board has a fiduciary duty to ma=
nage the company on behalf of all shareholders. Giving Musk a giant golden =
statue of himself is not necessary, or a good business decision, or fair to=
 the shareholders; it=E2=80=99s just the controlling shareholder fulfilling=
 his own whims with corporate money, and an ineffective board of directors =
giving him whatever he wants. He should have to give it back.=E2=80=9D And =
they will go to court, and the shareholders will make those arguments, and =
the board will say =E2=80=94=C2=A0accurately! =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cno yo=
u see giving him this giant golden statue is necessary for us to get more o=
f his incredibly valuable time and attention,=E2=80=9D and that will=C2=A0<=
em>sound bad=C2=A0</em>in court. And then a judge will get to decide whethe=
r the deal was fair to shareholders or not, and if it was not, the judge ca=
n make Musk pay the company back. Even if the board, and 99% of the shareho=
lders, want him to keep it!=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is some outside arbiter of what Musk is =
allowed to do at his public company, some standard of good behavior that ca=
n be enforced in court and that does not depend purely on the wishes of his=
 investors.=C2=A0Whereas at all his other companies it=E2=80=99s pretty muc=
h between him and his buddies, and they are=C2=A0indulgent.<a class=3D"foot=
